sentence: Consumer stocks were continuing to pace today's market following better-than-expected financial results from retailers Walmart ( WMT ), Home Depot ( HD ) and the TJX Companies ( TJX ), with shares of consumer staples companies in the S&P 500 rising over 0.4% while shares of consumer discretionary firms in the S&P 500 were ahead by nearly 0.9%.

In company news, Willis Lease Finance Corp. ( WLFC ) surged Tuesday after the airplane leasing company today began a modified Dutch auction tender offer, with plans to buy back up to 516,129 of its common shares at between $15.50 to $18.00 per share.
Overall, the company will cap the new stock repurchase program at $8 million.
The tender offer is slated to run through 5:00 p.m. on Dec. 16, unless extended or terminated early.
WLFC shares were up more than 9% this afternoon at $17.19 each, easing from a prior run to $17.47 a share.
(+) HD, (+4.2%) Adjusted Q3 EPS of $1.36 beats by $0.04 per share.
Revenue rises 6.4% to $21.82 bln, topping $21.77 bln consensus.
Guides FY16 earnings near high of prior forecast, expecting $5.36 per share after 5.7% sales increase to $87.92 bln; tops consensus expecting $5.36 per share on $87.73 bln in sales.
(-) DKS, (-9.8%) Q3 earnings of $0.45 per share, missing consenus by $0.01 per share.
Revenues grows 7.6% to $1.64 bln, also lagging $1.66 bln consensus.
Q4 EPS outlook of $1.10 to $1.25 trails Street view by at least $0.17.
Lowers FY16 EPS, comp sales forecasts below consensus.
